{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491216"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:38:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:38:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"883"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/883"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.6,0.01,0.23,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"883"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78211"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/883"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-11-05T09:21:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-22T09:43:58+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2025-05-20T14:58:10+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-18 03:56:33"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"883"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"22026"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63620"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"566"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1352"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36565"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63620"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78211","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78211"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of acute onset left-sided abdominal pain associated with nausea. Her last menstrual period was two weeks ago and she has noticed some vaginal spotting today. She has no significant medical history. Her only medication is a progesterone-only contraceptive pill. She is sexually active.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 70/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. There is tenderness in the left iliac fossa without guarding or rigidity. Speculum examination is unremarkable. Bimanual examination reveals left adnexal tenderness. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA urinary beta human chorionic gonadotropin test is negative. Complete blood count and biochemistry are within normal limits. Transvaginal ultrasound demonstrates several small ovarian cysts bilaterally with the largest measuring 25 mm in diameter, minimal free fluid, and no evidence of ovarian torsion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Polycystic ovarian syndrome","Ovarian cyst rupture","Diverticulitis","Mittelschmerz","Ectopic pregnancy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute unilateral pelvic pain and ultrasound findings consistent with ovarian cysts and free fluid. \u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian cyst rupture\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the acute onset of pain, mid-cycle timing, and presence of minimal free fluid on ultrasound. The negative pregnancy test and stable vital signs are reassuring features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolycystic ovarian syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic endocrine condition characterised by irregular menstrual cycles, hyperandrogenism, and polycystic ovarian morphology on ultrasound. While patients may have multiple small ovarian cysts, PCOS itself does not cause acute pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiverticulitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with left-sided abdominal pain but would be expected to have associated systemic symptoms such as fever and raised inflammatory markers. The normal blood tests and absence of bowel symptoms make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMittelschmerz\u003C/strong\u003E refers to physiological mid-cycle pain associated with ovulation. While the timing is appropriate, mittelschmerz is typically mild and self-limiting, not severe enough to prompt emergency presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEctopic pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E can present with unilateral pelvic pain and vaginal bleeding, but is effectively ruled out by the negative pregnancy test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of ovarian cyst rupture is typically conservative with analgesia and follow-up, provided the patient is haemodynamically stable and pain is controlled. Surgical intervention is rarely required unless there is significant bleeding or severe ongoing pain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ovarian cyst rupture typically presents with acute unilateral pelvic pain and minimal free fluid on ultrasound.","Mid-cycle timing and negative pregnancy test are important features distinguishing ovarian cyst rupture from ectopic pregnancy.","Most cases of ovarian cyst rupture can be managed conservatively with analgesia and outpatient follow-up."],"references":["Bottomley C, Bourne T. Diagnosis and management of ovarian cyst accidents. Best Pract Res Clin Obstet Gynaecol 2009; 23:711. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19299205/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63620"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"883"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63620"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T21:00:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-20T14:58:39+09:30","number":7,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-05-20T14:58:07+09:30","plagiarismScore":13.9,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-883-7.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250928%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250928T200836Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=915f5e11dddfca447d86bdbc963be62760b1eb55a3845b93e0ab4a9837e50bf5"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"883"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78211"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{